🚀 Day 21 – Complete CRUD API with Validation & Error Handling
📌 Overview

Successfully developed a fully functional CRUD API using ASP.NET Core with clean architecture.
The API includes data validation, structured error handling, and comprehensive test case coverage using Postman.

🧱 Architecture Used
Controller Layer
Service Layer
Repository Layer
DTO (Data Transfer Object) for validation
⚙️ Tech Stack
ASP.NET Core Web API
Entity Framework Core
SQL Server
Postman

🔧 Features Implemented
✅ CRUD Operations
➕ Create Employee
📄 Get All Employees
🔍 Get Employee by ID
✏️ Update Employee
❌ Delete Employee


🔐 Validation Implemented
✔ Name: Minimum 2 characters
✔ Email: Custom format (abc123@gmail.com)
✔ Phone: 10–15 digits only
✔ Status: Only Active or Inactive
✔ DOJ: Valid date format
✔ Required field validation for all inputs

🧪 Test Cases Covered
✅ Success Cases
Valid employee creation - employee created successfully 
Fetch all employees
Fetch employee by valid ID
Update employee successfully
Delete employee successfully

❌ Error Handling Cases
⛔ Empty request body
⛔ Missing required fields
⛔ Invalid email format
⛔ Invalid phone number
⛔ Invalid status value
⛔ Invalid date format
⛔ Multiple validation errors (handled together)
⛔ Employee not found (invalid ID)
⛔ Duplicate email/phone (service-level validation)

🛡️ Security & Best Practices
✔ DTO used to prevent over-posting
✔ Extra fields in request are ignored
✔ Input validation using DataAnnotations + Regex
✔ Service-level validation for business rules
✔ Clean separation of concerns

⚠️ Error Handling
Structured JSON response:
{
  "success": false,
  "message": "Validation failed",
  "errors": [
    { "message": "Invalid email format" }
  ]
}
Global exception handling implemented for system errors

🔁 API Flow
Client (Postman)
      ↓
Controller (DTO Validation)
      ↓
Service (Business Logic + Mapping)
      ↓
Repository (DB Operations)
      ↓
SQL Server

📊 Demo Highlights
✔ Live testing using Postman
